"ffdc1c","default":false,"description":""}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":7,"created_at":"2023-04-21T15:49:41Z","updated_at":"2026-05-15T10:53:34Z","closed_at":"2026-05-15T10:53:34Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","issue_field_values":[],"type":null,"active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"axum extra has its own `Multipart` type which does some borrow checking at runtime, making it possible to implement common and safe use cases. See https://github.com/tokio-rs/axum/pull/1692 for more context.\r\n\r\nFor 0.7 we should consider if we should promote that to axum.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokio-rs/axum/issues/1952/reactions","total_count":2,"+1":2,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokio-rs/axum/issues/1952/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"not_planned","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518/events","html_url":"https://github.com/gHashTag/t27/issues/518","id":4288003746,"node_id":"I_kwDOR5JM8M7_lb6i","number":518,"title":"feat(trios): scaffold gHashTag/trios — MCP git orchestrator server (CLI-first, GB-aware)","user":{"login":"gHashTag","id":6774813,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjY3NzQ4MTM=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/6774813?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag","html_url":"https://github.com/gHashTag","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/gHashTag/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":10601841601,"node_id":"LA_kwDOR5JM8M8AAAACd-tDwQ","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/labels/enhancement","name":"enhancement","color":"a2eeef","default":true,"description":"New feature or request"}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":1,"created_at":"2026-04-18T12:42:39Z","updated_at":"2026-04-20T19:07:55Z","closed_at":"2026-04-20T19:07:55Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"# TASK: Bootstrap `gHashTag/trios` — Agent-Controlled Git Orchestrator\n\n## Mission\n\nCreate `https://github.com/gHashTag/trios` — an MCP server that gives BrowserOS agents full CLI-level control over GitButler repositories.\n\n**PHI LOOP:** edit spec → seal hash → gen → test → verdict → save experience → skill commit → git commit\n\n---\n\n## Context\n\nGitButler is a Tauri app. CDP injection is impossible. **CLI-first is the only stable path.**\n\nThe agent does NOT control GitButler UI — it controls the repo via CLI, and GB UI updates itself via FSNotify file watcher.\n\nArchitecture:\n```\nBrowserOS Agent\n    │ A2A / MCP tool call\n    ▼\ntrios-server (port 9005) — MCP axum server\n    │ git2-rs (libgit2)\n    ├── git_status / git_stage / git_unstage / git_commit / git_create_branch\n    │ spawn process\n    └── gitbutler-cli (gHashTag/gitbutler fork)\n        └── gb_list_branches / gb_push_stack\n            │ writes to .git/\n            ▼\n        GitButler UI (auto-refreshes via FSNotify)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Invariant Laws (from t27 AGENTS.md — apply to trios too)\n\n| Law | Rule |\n|-----|------|\n| **L1** TRACEABILITY | Every PR must have `Closes #N` |\n| **L3** PURITY | ASCII-only source, English identifiers |\n| **L4** TESTABILITY | Every crate has `#[tokio::test]` coverage |\n| **L7** UNITY | NO `.sh` files — Rust commands only |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 0 — Reconnaissance (Day 1)\n\n**Agent action:**\n1. Clone `https://github.com/gHashTag/gitbutler`\n2. Run `gitbutler-cli --help`, document available commands\n3. List `crates/gitbutler-cli/src/` — identify JSON output flags\n\n**Deliverable:** `experience/trios/phase0-gb-cli-audit.trinity` — list of available CLI commands + JSON flags\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Scaffold `gHashTag/trios` (Day 1)\n\nCreate repo with this workspace structure:\n\n```\ntrios/\n├── Cargo.toml              # workspace\n├── crates/\n│   ├── trios-core/         # types, constants, traits (GitOrchestrator)\n│   ├── trios-git/          # impl via git2-rs\n│   ├── trios-gb/           # wrapper over gitbutler-cli\n│   └── trios-server/       # MCP server (axum, port 9005)\n├── .github/workflows/ci.yml  # cargo test + clippy -D warnings\n├── CLAUDE.md               # agent laws (NO .sh, issue gate, TDD)\n└── README.md\n```\n\n**CLAUDE.md laws:**\n- NO `.sh` files — Rust/TS only\n- Every PR: `Closes #N`\n- `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` = 0\n- `cargo test` passes before merge\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — `trios-core` + `trios-git` (Days 2–3)\n\nCore trait:\n\n```rust\npub trait GitOrchestrator {\n    async fn status(&self, repo_path: &Path) -> Result<Vec<FileStatus>>;\n    async fn stage(&self, repo_path: &Path, paths: &[&Path]) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn commit(&self, repo_path: &Path, message: &str) -> Result<CommitOid>;\n    async fn create_branch(&self, repo_path: &Path, name: &str) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn switch_branch(&self, repo_path: &Path, name: &str) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn push(&self, repo_path: &Path, remote: &str, branch: &str) -> Result<()>;\n}\n```\n\n**TDD requirement:** each method covered by `#[tokio::test]` using `tempdir`.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — `trios-gb` (Days 4–5)\n\nWrap `gitbutler-cli` for GB-specific ops (virtual branches, stacks).\n\nFallback: if `gitbutler-cli` not found → return `Err` with clear message, server continues without GB tools.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — `trios-server` MCP (Days 6–8)\n\nAxum server on port 9005. MVP: **7 tools**\n\n| Tool | Source | Action |\n|------|--------|--------|\n| `git_status` | git2-rs | list changed files |\n| `git_stage_files` | git2-rs | stage by paths |\n| `git_unstage_files` | git2-rs | unstage |\n| `git_commit` | git2-rs | commit with message |\n| `git_create_branch` | git2-rs | new branch |\n| `gb_list_branches` | gitbutler-cli | virtual GB branches |\n| `gb_push_stack` | gitbutler-cli | push stack |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 5 — BrowserOS Integration (Days 9–10)\n\nAdd trios as MCP server in `BrowserOS/packages/browseros-agent/apps/server/src/strata-proxy.ts`:\n\n```typescript\nconst triosClient = new MCPClient({\n  url: \"http://localhost:9005/mcp\",\n  name: \"trios-git\",\n})\n```\n\n---\n\n## What NOT to do\n\n- ❌ No CDP injection into GitButler\n- ❌ No `.sh` scripts anywhere\n- ❌ No merge without `cargo test` passing\n- ❌ No duplicate tools (trios-server ≠ BrowserOS tools)\n- ❌ No monolith — each crate compiles + tests independently\n\n---\n\n## Timeline\n\n```\nDay 1:   Phase 0 + 1 — scaffold trios, audit gitbutler-cli\nDays 2-3: Phase 2 — trios-git (libgit2, tests)\nDays 4-5: Phase 3 — trios-gb (CLI wrapper)\nDays 6-8: Phase 4 — trios-server (MCP axum)\nDay 9:   Phase 5 — BrowserOS integration\nDay 10:  Demo — agent commits files from screenshot via chat\n```\n\n---\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- [ ] `cargo test` passes across all crates\n- [ ] `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` = 0 errors\n- [ ] `git_stage_files` + `git_commit` callable via MCP POST\n- [ ] BrowserOS agent can commit a file by chat command\n- [ ] `experience/trios/` has `.trinity` SSOT entries for each phase\n\n---\n\n**φ² + 1/φ² = 3 | TRINITY | GO.**\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gHashTag/t27/issues/518/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/events","html_url":"https://github.com/madmax983/autumn/issues/592","id":4368004368,"node_id":"I_kwDORsxAfc8AAAABBFp1EA","number":592,"title":"Certify examples as runnable user journeys","user":{"login":"madmax983","id":1848860,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE4NDg4NjA=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1848860?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983","html_url":"https://github.com/madmax983","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/madmax983/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":10798315812,"node_id":"LA_kwDORsxAfc8AAAACg6E5JA","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/labels/spec","name":"spec","color":"0e8a16","default":false,"description":"PM specification awaiting engineering"},{"id":10798315907,"node_id":"LA_kwDORsxAfc8AAAACg6E5gw","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/labels/pm","name":"pm","color":"fbca04","default":false,"description":"Authored by Vantage / product management"}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2026-05-02T05:06:26Z","updated_at":"2026-05-10T03:08:34Z","closed_at":"2026-05-10T03:08:34Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"## Problem (the \"So What?\")\nAutumn's examples are the proof that the framework can ship real applications, not just expose clever primitives. Today the README, workspace membership, docs, and `examples/` directory can drift: for example, `examples/canopy` exists locally but is not listed in the workspace or README example table. That ambiguity turns examples from adoption assets into trust debt, especially for evaluators comparing Autumn against Rails/Phoenix/Loco where the guided app path is part of the product.\n\n## User Story\nAs a framework user evaluating Autumn, I want every advertised example to be clearly cataloged, runnable, and tied to a specific user journey, so that I can pick the closest starting point and prove the framework works without spelunking source folders or guessing which examples are blessed.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A single documented examples catalog lists every supported example with its target persona, demonstrated journey, key Autumn capabilities, prerequisites, exact run command, and expected first successful request or page.\n- [ ] Every example advertised in `README.md`, `docs/guide/*`, or the tutorial appears in the catalog with the same name and purpose.\n- [ ] Every cataloged example is either a workspace member that participates in the normal example validation path, or is explicitly marked as external/manual with a reason and a documented smoke command.\n- [ ] Every directory under `examples/` is either cataloged as supported or explicitly marked experimental/scratch/excluded with a short rationale; unmarked orphan directories fail the documented release check.\n- [ ] Each supported example has a README quickstart from clean checkout to first successful request, including required services such as Postgres or Redis and the exact command that proves success.\n- [ ] The release checklist includes a machine-checkable example drift gate that catches README/catalog/workspace mismatches before publishing `autumn-web` or `autumn-cli`.\n- [ ] The validation output groups examples by support tier, so a contributor can immediately see which failures block release and which are intentionally manual.\n- [ ] The catalog maps current examples to distinct journeys rather than repeating the same CRUD story: first route, CRUD app, admin/static rendering, profiles/tasks, distributed deployment, hooks/revisions, full-stack reddit clone, custom config loading, and WebSocket echo.\n- [ ] Generated artifacts such as compiled CSS are not treated as source-of-truth for the catalog; example status is owned by docs and validation metadata.\n- [ ] This adds no new public `autumn-web` API and does not require downstream app migration.\n\n## Success Metric\nA new evaluator can choose the right supported example and reach its documented first successful request in under **3 minutes** after prerequisites are running. The release drift gate catches **100%** of unlisted `examples/` directories and README/catalog/workspace mismatches before a release is cut.\n\n## Out of Scope\n- Adding a new showcase application.\n- Rewriting existing examples to demonstrate new framework features.\n- Browser end-to-end testing or screenshot regression testing.\n- The canonical downstream app integration testing story; #513 owns that.\n- Generated auth, admin adapters, jobs dashboards, or plugin conformance; #588, #590, #585, and #591 own those product surfaces.\n- Changing the published `autumn-web` API or crate layout.\n\n## Gap Analysis\n- **axum** — the official repo positions axum as an ergonomic, modular library and points users at examples and community showcases, but it does not need a certified app-journey catalog because axum is not promising a batteries-included app framework: https://github.com/tokio-rs/axum.\n- **actix-web** — Actix has a large community examples repository, which is useful breadth, but it reads like ecosystem samples rather than a curated framework adoption path: https://github.com/actix/examples.\n- **rocket** — Rocket's guide is strong as a tutorial/reference, but Rocket does not currently compete on a Rails-style catalog of runnable full-stack example journeys: https://rocket.rs/guide.\n- **loco.rs** — Loco is the closest Rust peer: starters, generated commands, routes, doctor, testing docs, and template choices make the app journey explicit. Autumn has richer server-rendered examples, but without catalog certification the advantage is harder for users to see: https://loco.rs/docs/getting-started/starters/.\n- **leptos** — Leptos has starter templates and examples for full-stack/SSR/CSR Rust UI apps, but its examples serve a different product promise: reactive UI and hydration rather than Autumn's server-first Rails/Spring shape: https://github.com/leptos-rs.\n- **Rails** — Rails' getting-started guide creates a concrete blog app and teaches the app shape as the canonical adoption path. Autumn's examples should play the same role, but with multiple certified journeys instead of one tutorial app: https://guides.rubyonrails.org/getting_started.html.\n- **Phoenix** — Phoenix generated apps and resources come with tests and real examples, which makes the generated journey self-verifying. Autumn should copy the product principle, not the implementation: every blessed example should prove its journey still runs: https://hexdocs.pm/phoenix/testing.html.\n- **Django** — Django's tutorial series carries the example through tests and reusable-app packaging, reinforcing that examples are maintained teaching artifacts, not throwaway folders: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/intro/reusable-apps/.\n- **The autumn-shaped answer** — treat examples as part of the product surface. A supported example is a promise: documented purpose, exact run path, known prerequisites, drift checks, and a clear support tier. If an example is scratch work, mark it as such or keep it out of the adoption path.\n\n## Complexity Tier\nM — touches documentation, release validation, and example metadata across the workspace; no public API impact and no downstream migration burden, but multi-service examples make the validation matrix more than a one-file cleanup.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/madmax983/autumn/issues/592/timeline","performed_via_github_app":{"id":1144995,"client_id":"Iv23liVemv8A9if9v0F2","slug":"chatgpt-codex-connector","node_id":"A_kwHOAOQ6Gs4AEXij","owner":{"login":"openai","id":14957082,"node_id":"MDEyOk9yZ2FuaXphdGlvbjE0OTU3MDgy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/14957082?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai","html_url":"https://gith